mmigrants themselves, but also everyday understandings of race and racism within the United States and Mexico. Within their communities and networks that span an international border, Zamora argues, immigrants come to define "race" in a way distinct from both the color-conscious hierarchy of Mexican society and the Black-White binary prevalent within the United States. In the process, their stories demonstrate how race is not static, but rather an evolving social phenomenon forever altered by immigration.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aImmigrantszUnited StatesxSocial conditions. 0aMexicansxRace identityzUnited States. 0aMexicanszUnited StatesxSocial conditions. 0aRacismzMexico. 0aRacismzUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Emigration & Immigration.2bisacsh  aLatino.  aMexican migration.  aMexico.  aimmigration.  amestizaje.  arace and ethnicity.  arace relations.  aracial hierarchy.  aracialization.  atransnationalism.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022 Englishz978311099389908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022z9783110994810oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Sociology 2022 Englishz978311099455108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Sociology 2022z9783110994520oZDB-23-DSL08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertStanford University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z97831107664860 cprintz978150362852640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150363225740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503632257423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781503632257/original  a978-3-11-076648-6  Stanford University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  a978-3-11-099389-9  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022 Englishb2022  a978-3